# Unit Test Patterns

Write unit tests in this pattern when possible.

## Single Assert per Test

Each test method should have exactly one assertion. This keeps tests focused and makes failures easier to diagnose.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD - multiple asserts
[Test]
public void ParsesCorrectly()
{
    Assert.That(_actual[0].Text, Is.EqualTo("foo"));
    Assert.That(_actual[0].Ordinal, Is.EqualTo(1));
}

// ✅ GOOD - one assert each
[Test]
public void Step0_HasExpectedText() => Assert.That(_actual[0].Text, Is.EqualTo(ExpectedStep0Text));

[Test]
public void Step0_HasExpectedOrdinal() => Assert.That(_actual[0].Ordinal, Is.EqualTo(ExpectedStep0Ordinal));
```

## Shared Setup

Use `[OneTimeSetUp]` or `[SetUp]` to share expensive setup across tests. Prefer `OneTimeSetUp` when setup is immutable.

```csharp
private List<Result> _actual = [];

[OneTimeSetUp]
public void OneTimeSetup()
{
    _actual = Sut.Parse(Input);
}
```

## Constants for Reuse

Extract expected values into constants. Derive inputs from expected outputs when possible so expected values are the single source of truth.

```csharp
private const int ExpectedStepCount = 5;
private const string ExpectedStep0Text = "1. Place oven on broil";
private const string ExpectedStep1Text = "2. Mix ingredients";
private const string InputWithNoNewlines = ExpectedStep0Text + ExpectedStep1Text;
```

## Scenario-Based Class Organization

Structure test classes around scenarios (e.g. `WhenStepsAreNumbered`, `WhenStepsAreMissing`). Use descriptive test names that read like specifications.
